Fixing this will allow us to write to a file to support storage.

We add the required constructors that enable setting of boolean isDone and method toFileFormat()

commitResults.messageTitle: Support reading from and writing to file
commitResults.messageBody:
Elara did not support reading to and writing from file, so user has to
retype todo list every time Elara is run

Restructuring Elara by adding methods to read files, parse files for
tasks and save tasks to file allows us to store the data in a specified
file.

Let's reorganise code for Elara by breaking up into smaller blocks
and add methods readFile(), setupFile(), parseTask() and
saveTasksToFile().

commitResults.messageTitle: Update DeadlineTaskException and EventException error message
commitResults.messageBody:
Previous error message did not specify format for deadline and start and end
time for deadline and event tasks.

Updating the error messages allows users to know the proper format to send into
Elara such that they can efficiently use the task list.

Let's update the error message to include the format to parse for LocalDateTime

commitResults.messageTitle: Change format for deadlines and event start and end to LocalDateTime
commitResults.messageBody:
The previous type for storing deadlines and event timings was String, which
does not allow for more meaningful storage.

Changing the type to LocalDateTime allows the chatbot to understand that
it is a date and time instead of just a String.

Let's edit the DeadlineTask and EventTask variables to reflect this, as well
as change the format of parseTask() to support reading such data from files.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor code to extract out closely related code as classes
commitResults.messageBody:
Main class Elara is very long and messy due to a lot of similar code.

Splitting the code into different classes allows for modularisation and easier debugging.

Let's implement the classes and Command interface.

commitResults.messageTitle: Divide classes into packages
commitResults.messageBody:
Classes are currently located in the root package without clear
organization.

This unstructured organization makes the codebase harder to navigate
and maintain. It violates OOP principles of encapsulation and
modularity, making it difficult to locate related classes and
understand the overall architecture.

Divide classes into specific packages based on their functionality:
- Move command-related classes (`Command`, `AddCommand`, `ListCommand`,
  etc.) into a `command` package.
- Place task-related classes (`Task`, `ToDoTask`, `DeadlineTask`,
  `EventTask`) and exception classes (`InvalidInputException`,
  `ToDoException`, `DeadlineException`, `EventException`) into a `task`
  package.
- Organize file handling classes (`Storage`) into a `storage` package.
- Group user interaction classes (`Ui`) into a `ui` package.
- Consolidate parsing logic (`Parser`) into a `parser` package.

This organization follows OOP principles, promoting encapsulation and
modularity. It makes the codebase more readable, maintainable, and
scalable by logically grouping related functionalities. Future
development and troubleshooting will be easier, as classes will be
clearly categorized and located.

No functional changes are introduced; this refactor strictly improves
the project structure.

commitResults.messageTitle: Automate project builds using Gradle
commitResults.messageBody:
Project builds are currently managed manually without a standardized
build automation tool.

This manual process is error-prone and inefficient, making it harder
to manage dependencies, compile code, run tests, and package
distributions consistently. It slows down development and increases
the likelihood of build-related errors.

Automate project builds using Gradle:
- Add a `build.gradle` file to define project dependencies and build
  configurations.
- Include Gradle wrapper files to standardize the Gradle version used
  across different development environments.
- Configure tasks for compiling code, running tests, and packaging the
  application into distributable formats.

Using Gradle provides a standardized build process, improving
consistency and reliability. It simplifies dependency management,
reduces setup time for new developers, and facilitates integration
with CI/CD pipelines.

This change ensures that all developers and CI systems use the same
build process, enhancing collaboration and project stability.

Edit the code to comply with Java coding standards
commitResults.messageBody:
The current code does not fully comply with Java coding standards,
particularly in variable naming conventions such as the usage of
camelCase for private final variables.

This needs to change to improve code consistency, readability, and
ensure it follows widely accepted Java conventions, making it easier
for developers to understand and maintain.

Refactored variable names like `FILE_PATH` to use camelCase as per
Java standards. Private final variables now adhere to the camelCase
convention.

This approach ensures the codebase is easier to read and maintain,
and that it conforms to industry-standard Java naming practices.

No functional changes were made; this commit is purely a style
refactor for standardization.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add find command for searching tasks by keyword
commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, there is no way for users to search for tasks
based on a keyword in the task description. This makes it
difficult to find specific tasks quickly, especially when
there are many tasks.

This needs to change to improve the user experience by
allowing users to filter tasks based on a keyword, making
task management more efficient.

A new FindCommand class has been implemented to handle the
'find' command. The Parser has been updated to recognize the
'find' command and parse the search keyword. A findTasks
method has been added to the TaskList class to return tasks
matching the keyword. The Ui class now includes a method
to display the matching tasks to the user.

This approach was chosen to align with the existing command
pattern, keeping the code modular and easily extensible.

commitResults.messageTitle: Configure Checkstyle for code quality checks
commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, there is no automated way to enforce coding standards in the project.

To ensure consistency and detect coding style violations, Checkstyle is introduced.
The configuration files (checkstyle.xml and suppressions.xml) are added under config/checkstyle,
and necessary changes are made to the build.gradle file to integrate Checkstyle into the build process.

This will allow the project to maintain a high standard of code quality and detect issues early during development.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor code to comply with Checkstyle standards
commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, the code does not fully adhere to the coding standards enforced by Checkstyle,
which has led to violations during code quality checks.

This commit refactors the code to ensure it complies with the Checkstyle configuration.
Changes include adjustments to import order, line breaks, spacing, as well as the addition of necessary Javadoc comments.

Ensuring compliance with Checkstyle helps maintain a consistent coding style across the project and improves readability and maintainability.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update build.gradle to support JavaFX integration
commitResults.messageBody:
The current build.gradle configuration does not include support for JavaFX,
which is required for the graphical user interface components of the project.

This commit updates the build.gradle file to include the necessary dependencies
and configurations for JavaFX. It adds the JavaFX plugin and specifies the version
and modules required for the project.

This ensures that the project can successfully compile and run JavaFX applications,
enabling the development of rich desktop applications with a graphical interface.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add FXML files for JavaFX interface components
commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, the project lacks the necessary FXML files to define the structure of the JavaFX interface.

This commit adds `DialogBox.fxml` and `MainWindow.fxml` to the resources/view directory,
which define the layout for the dialog boxes and the main window interface in the JavaFX application.

This ensures that the project has the required layout files to support JavaFX-based user interface components.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor package structure and update Ui methods
commitResults.messageBody:
Files like `Parser.java` and `Storage.java` are scattered across
different packages, leading to inconsistencies in project structure.

To maintain a clean and organized codebase, files related to command
execution and components should be grouped in one package.

The files `Parser.java`, `Storage.java`, and `UnmarkCommand.java` have
been moved to the `components` package. Additionally, the methods in
`Ui.java` that previously printed messages directly have been refactored
to return strings instead. This enhances flexibility and supports better
unit testing by decoupling UI logic from direct console printing.

This approach improves maintainability and allows for better
modularization of the system.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor package structure and update Ui methods
commitResults.messageBody:
The current situation involves files spread across different packages,
leading to challenges in maintaining consistency across imports and
method calls.

To streamline and centralize the code, files from various packages were
moved to a unified utils package. This simplifies imports and enhances
maintainability by keeping related components together.

Additionally, methods in Ui.java were updated to return strings
instead of printing directly. This approach improves flexibility in
handling output, making it easier to test and reuse components.
The task.getDescription() method was also added to support these
changes.

These changes were made to ensure consistency in the code structure
and improve the systemâ€™s modularity.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update methods in Ui.java
commitResults.messageBody:
The current situation is that the `Ui` class returns strings for
displayed messages rather than printing them directly, which limits
flexibility in how these messages are used or tested.

The code needs to be updated to improve flexibility by displaying
messages directly instead of returning them as strings. This change
allows for more seamless interaction within the program and centralizes
the logic related to handling outputs.

To address this, I modified methods in the `Ui` class to print messages
directly to the console rather than returning them as strings. I also
introduced a `lastResponse` field to keep track of the most recent
message for testing or further use.

This approach enhances clarity and makes the user interface code more
streamlined while allowing access to the last printed message for
testing purposes or other internal uses.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add newline at the end of TaskList.java
commitResults.messageBody:
The TaskList.java file was missing a newline at the end, which is a
standard coding convention for better readability and to avoid issues
with version control systems that may flag it as a change.

A newline has been added at the end of TaskList.java to comply with
Java coding standards and maintain consistency across files.

This change ensures that the file conforms to best practices.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add new JavaFX components for GUI support
commitResults.messageBody:
The following files were added to support the graphical user interface
for Elara:

- DialogBox.java: Defines the structure and behavior for chat dialog
  boxes in the UI.
- Launcher.java: Handles the application launch.
- Main.java: Entry point for the JavaFX application.
- MainWindow.java: Contains the layout and control logic for the
  main window.

These additions provide the foundational components needed for the
Elara chatbot's graphical interface, enhancing user interaction
and experience.
